<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 2: WHY THIS AREA
════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2ead4); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b98229; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#191817; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">Acreage lifestyle, city boundary: the outer north's most semi-rural suburb.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Upper Kedron occupies a genuinely distinctive position in Brisbane's outer northern corridor. It is the suburb that sits at the metropolitan edge, adjacent to D'Aguilar National Park, with a semi-rural character that sets it apart from even its immediate neighbours Keperra and Ferny Grove. Buyers who come to Upper Kedron have typically made a specific lifestyle decision: they want more space, more privacy, and a semi-rural setting, and they have decided that the Brisbane city boundary is the right place to find it. Large and acreage-style blocks, elevated terrain and quiet streets are the defining features. The trade-off for that space is a slightly longer commute, and the working-from-home shift has made that trade-off far more acceptable to a broader range of buyers.
    </p>
