<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I understand what draws buyers to Upper Kedron and what they expect when they arrive to inspect. The buyer who targets this suburb has already worked through the question of space versus proximity and landed firmly on space. Presentation and accurate pricing matter because these buyers are deliberate and focused: they will discount quickly for deferred maintenance but compete hard for a property that delivers on the semi-rural promise they came for.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Upper Kedron's large and acreage-style blocks are the defining feature of the suburb. Block size is the primary value driver here, not micro-position within the suburb in the way that elevation matters in Ferny Grove. A genuinely large block with privacy, tree cover and space creates a sub-market that draws buyers who have specifically decided that an acreage lifestyle within Brisbane's metropolitan boundary is what they want. That scarcity is real: there are very few suburbs within the city limits that offer this combination. The Ferny Grove State High School catchment connection also drives family-upgrader demand from buyers who want both the school and the space. Nearby Keperra and Ferny Grove train stations give commuters a viable rail option on days when they need to travel, and the suburb's proximity to D'Aguilar National Park means that residents have access to trails and bushland that is genuinely rare at this distance from the CBD.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
